# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantum-chemistry-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The basis set can either be composed of atomic orbitals (yielding the linear combination of atomic orbitals approach), which is the usual choice within the quantum chemistry community; plane waves which are typically used within the solid state community, or real-space approaches.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Several types of atomic orbitals can be used: Gaussian-type orbitals, Slater-type orbitals, or numerical atomic orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Out of the three, Gaussian-type orbitals are by far the most often used, as they allow efficient implementations of post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In modern computational chemistry, quantum chemical calculations are performed using a finite set of basis functions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] When the finite basis is expanded towards an (infinite) complete set of functions, calculations using such a basis set are said to approach the complete basis set (CBS) limit.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In this context, *basis function* and *atomic orbital* are sometimes used interchangeably, although the basis functions are usually not true atomic orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Within the basis set, the wavefunction is represented as a vector, the components of which correspond to coefficients of the basis functions in the linear expansion.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In such a basis, one-electron operators correspond to matrices (a.k.a. rank two tensors), whereas two-electron operators are rank four tensors.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] When molecular calculations are performed, it is common to use a basis composed of atomic orbitals, centered at each nucleus within the molecule (linear combination of atomic orbitals ansatz).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The physically best motivated basis set are Slater-type orbitals (STOs), which are solutions to the Schrödinger equation of hydrogen-like atoms, and decay exponentially far away from the nucleus.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] It can be shown that the molecular orbitals of Hartree–Fock and density-functional theory also exhibit exponential decay.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, S-type STOs also satisfy Kato's cusp condition at the nucleus, meaning that they are able to accurately describe electron density near the nucleus.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, hydrogen-like atoms lack many-electron interactions, thus the orbitals do not accurately describe electron state correlations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Unfortunately, calculating integrals with STOs is computationally difficult and it was later realized by Frank Boys that STOs could be approximated as linear combinations of Gaussian-type orbitals (GTOs) instead.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Because the product of two GTOs can be written as a linear combination of GTOs, integrals with Gaussian basis functions can be written in closed form, which leads to huge computational savings (see John Pople).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Dozens of Gaussian-type orbital basis sets have been published in the literature.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets typically come in hierarchies of increasing size, giving a controlled way to obtain more accurate solutions, however at a higher cost.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The smallest basis sets are called *minimal basis sets*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set is one in which, on each atom in the molecule, a single basis function is used for each orbital in a Hartree–Fock calculation on the free atom.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For atoms such as lithium, basis functions of p type are also added to the basis functions that correspond to the 1s and 2s orbitals of the free atom, because lithium also has a 1s2p bound state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For example, each atom in the second period of the periodic system (Li – Ne) would have a basis set of five functions (two s functions and three p functions).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set may already be exact for the gas-phase atom at the self-consistent field level of theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In the next level, additional functions are added to describe polarization of the electron density of the atom in molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] These are called **polarization functions**.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For example, while the minimal basis set for hydrogen is one function approximating the 1s atomic orbital, a simple polarized basis set typically has two s- and one p-function (which consists of three basis functions: px, py and pz).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This adds flexibility to the basis set, effectively allowing molecular orbitals involving the hydrogen atom to be more asymmetric about the hydrogen nucleus.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This is very important for modeling chemical bonding, because the bonds are often polarized.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly, d-type functions can be added to a basis set with valence p orbitals, and f-functions to a basis set with d-type orbitals, and so on.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Another common addition to basis sets is the addition of **diffuse functions**.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] These are extended Gaussian basis functions with a small exponent, which give flexibility to the "tail" portion of the atomic orbitals, far away from the nucleus.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse basis functions are important for describing anions or dipole moments, but they can also be important for accurate modeling of intra- and inter-molecular bonding.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The most common minimal basis set is STO-nG, where n is an integer.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The STO-nG basis sets are derived from a minimal Slater-type orbital basis set, with *n* representing the number of Gaussian primitive functions used to represent each Slater-type orbital.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Minimal basis sets typically give rough results that are insufficient for research-quality publication, but are much cheaper than their larger counterparts.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] There are several other minimum basis sets that have been used such as the MidiX basis sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] During most molecular bonding, it is the valence electrons which principally take part in the bonding.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In recognition of this fact, it is common to represent valence orbitals by more than one basis function (each of which can in turn be composed of a fixed linear combination of primitive Gaussian functions).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets in which there are multiple basis functions corresponding to each valence atomic orbital are called valence double, triple, quadruple-zeta, and so on, basis sets (zeta, ζ, was commonly used to represent the exponent of an STO basis function).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Since the different orbitals of the split have different spatial extents, the combination allows the electron density to adjust its spatial extent appropriate to the particular molecular environment.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, minimal basis sets lack the flexibility to adjust to different molecular environments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The notation for the *split-valence* basis sets arising from the group of John Pople is typically *X-YZg*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, *X* represents the number of primitive Gaussians comprising each core atomic orbital basis function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The *Y* and *Z* indicate that the valence orbitals are composed of two basis functions each, the first one composed of a linear combination of *Y* primitive Gaussian functions, the other composed of a linear combination of *Z* primitive Gaussian functions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, the presence of two numbers after the hyphens implies that this basis set is a *split-valence double-zeta* basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Split-valence triple- and quadruple-zeta basis sets are also used, denoted as *X-YZWg*, *X-YZWVg*, etc.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Polarization functions are denoted by two different notations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The original Pople notation added "*" to indicate that all "heavy" atoms (everything but H and He) have a small set of polarization functions added to the basis (in the case of carbon, a set of 3d orbital functions).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The "**" notation indicates that all "light" atoms also receive polarization functions (this adds a set of 2p orbitals to the basis for each hydrogen atom).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Eventually it became desirable to add more polarization to the basis sets, and a new notation was developed in which the number and types of polarization functions are given explicitly in parentheses in the order (heavy,light) but with the principal quantum numbers of the orbitals implicit.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the * notation becomes (d) and the ** notation is now given as (d,p).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] If instead 3d and 4f functions were added to each heavy atom and 2p, 3p, 3d functions were added to each light atom, the notation would become (df,2pd).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In all cases, diffuse functions are indicated by either adding a + before the letter G (diffuse functions on heavy atoms only) or ++ (diffuse functions are added to all atoms).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The Pople basis sets were originally developed for use in Hartree-Fock calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Since then, correlation-consistent or polarization-consistent basis sets (see below) have been developed which are usually more appropriate for correlated wave function calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the most widely used basis sets are those developed by Dunning and coworkers, since they are designed for converging post-Hartree–Fock calculations systematically to the complete basis set limit using empirical extrapolation techniques.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For first- and second-row atoms, the basis sets are cc-pVNZ where *N* = *D*,*T*,*Q*,5,6,...
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The 'cc-p', stands for 'correlation-consistent polarized' and the 'V' indicates that only basis sets for the valence orbitals are of multiple-zeta quality.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] (Like the Pople basis sets, the core orbitals are of single-zeta quality.) They include successively larger shells of polarization (correlating) functions (*d*, *f*, *g*, etc.).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] More recently these 'correlation-consistent polarized' basis sets have become widely used and are the current state of the art for correlated or post-Hartree–Fock calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The *aug-* prefix is added if diffuse functions are included in the basis.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For period-3 atoms (Al–Ar), additional functions have turned out to be necessary; these are the cc-pV(N+d)Z basis sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Even larger atoms may employ pseudopotential basis sets, cc-pVNZ-PP, or relativistic-contracted Douglas-Kroll basis sets, cc-pVNZ-DK.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] While the usual Dunning basis sets are for valence-only calculations, the sets can be augmented with further functions that describe core electron correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] These core-valence sets (cc-pCVXZ) can be used to approach the exact solution to the all-electron problem, and they are necessary for accurate geometric and nuclear property calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Weighted core-valence sets (cc-pwCVXZ) have also been recently suggested.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The weighted sets aim to capture core-valence correlation, while neglecting most of core-core correlation, in order to yield accurate geometries with smaller cost than the cc-pCVXZ sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse functions can also be added for describing anions and long-range interactions such as Van der Waals forces, or to perform electronic excited-state calculations, electric field property calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] A recipe for constructing additional augmented functions exists; as many as five augmented functions have been used in second hyperpolarizability calculations in the literature.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Because of the rigorous construction of these basis sets, extrapolation can be done for almost any energetic property.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, care must be taken when extrapolating energy differences as the individual energy components converge at different rates: the Hartree–Fock energy converges exponentially, whereas the correlation energy converges only polynomially.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] To understand how to get the number of functions, consider the cc-pVDZ basis set for H: There are two *s* (*L* = 0) orbitals and one *p* (*L* = 1) orbital that has 3 angular-momentum components along the *z*-axis (*m*L = −1,0,1) corresponding to *p**x*, *p**y* and *p**z*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Thus, there are five spatial orbitals in total.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Note that each orbital can hold two electrons of opposite spin.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] As another example, Ar [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p] has 3 s orbitals (*L* = 0) and 2 sets of p orbitals (*L* = 1).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Using cc-pVDZ, orbitals are [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3s, 3p, 3p, 3d'] (where ' represents the added in polarisation orbitals), with 4 s orbitals (4 basis functions), 3 sets of p orbitals (3 × 3 = 9 basis functions), and 1 set of d orbitals (5 basis functions).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Adding up the basis functions gives a total of 18 functions for Ar with the cc-pVDZ basis-set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Density-functional theory has recently become widely used in computational chemistry.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, the correlation-consistent basis sets described above are suboptimal for density-functional theory, because the correlation-consistent sets have been designed for post-Hartree–Fock, while density-functional theory exhibits much more rapid basis set convergence than wave function methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Adopting a similar methodology to the correlation-consistent series, Frank Jensen introduced polarization-consistent (pc-n) basis sets as a way to quickly converge density functional theory calculations to the complete basis set limit.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Like the Dunning sets, the pc-n sets can be combined with basis set extrapolation techniques to obtain CBS values.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The pc-n sets can be augmented with diffuse functions to obtain augpc-n sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the various valence adaptations of Karlsruhe basis sets are briefly described below.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Gaussian-type orbital basis sets are typically optimized to reproduce the lowest possible energy for the systems used to train the basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, the convergence of the energy does not imply convergence of other properties, such as nuclear magnetic shieldings, the dipole moment, or the electron momentum density, which probe different aspects of the electronic wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Manninen and Vaara have proposed completeness-optimized basis sets, where the exponents are obtained by maximization of the one-electron completeness profile instead of minimization of the energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are a way to easily approach the complete basis set limit of any property at any level of theory, and the procedure is simple to automatize.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are tailored to a specific property.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This way, the flexibility of the basis set can be focused on the computational demands of the chosen property, typically yielding much faster convergence to the complete basis set limit than is achievable with energy-optimized basis sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Here, only the two parameters $\alpha _{l}$ and $\beta _{l}$ must be optimized, significantly reducing the dimension of the search space or even avoiding the exponent optimization problem.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In order to properly describe electronic delocalized states, a previously optimized standard basis set can be complemented with additional delocalized Gaussian functions with small exponent values, generated by the even-tempered scheme.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This approach has also been employed to generate basis sets for other types of quantum particles rather than electrons, like quantum nuclei, negative muons or positrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In addition to localized basis sets, plane-wave basis sets can also be used in quantum-chemical simulations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Typically, the choice of the plane wave basis set is based on a cutoff energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the simulation cell that fit below the energy criterion are then included in the calculation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] These basis sets are popular in calculations involving three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The main advantage of a plane-wave basis is that it is guaranteed to converge in a *smooth, monotonic manner* to the target wavefunction.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, when localized basis sets are used, monotonic convergence to the basis set limit may be difficult due to problems with over-completeness: in a large basis set, functions on different atoms start to look alike, and many eigenvalues of the overlap matrix approach zero.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In addition, certain integrals and operations are much easier to program and carry out with plane-wave basis functions than with their localized counterparts.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the kinetic energy operator is diagonal in the reciprocal space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Integrals over real-space operators can be efficiently carried out using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The properties of the Fourier Transform allow a vector representing the gradient of the total energy with respect to the plane-wave coefficients to be calculated with a computational effort that scales as NPW*ln(NPW) where NPW is the number of plane-waves.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] When this property is combined with separable pseudopotentials of the Kleinman-Bylander type and pre-conditioned conjugate gradient solution techniques, the dynamic simulation of periodic problems containing hundreds of atoms becomes possible.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In practice, plane-wave basis sets are often used in combination with an 'effective core potential' or pseudopotential, so that the plane waves are only used to describe the valence charge density.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This is because core electrons tend to be concentrated very close to the atomic nuclei, resulting in large wavefunction and density gradients near the nuclei which are not easily described by a plane-wave basis set unless a very high energy cutoff, and therefore small wavelength, is used.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This combined method of a plane-wave basis set with a core pseudopotential is often abbreviated as a *PSPW* calculation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, as all functions in the basis are mutually orthogonal and are not associated with any particular atom, plane-wave basis sets do not exhibit basis-set superposition error.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane-wave basis set is dependent on the size of the simulation cell, complicating cell size optimization.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Due to the assumption of periodic boundary conditions, plane-wave basis sets are less well suited to gas-phase calculations than localized basis sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Large regions of vacuum need to be added on all sides of the gas-phase molecule in order to avoid interactions with the molecule and its periodic copies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane waves use a similar accuracy to describe the vacuum region as the region where the molecule is, meaning that obtaining the truly noninteracting limit may be computationally costly.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] A combination of some of the properties of localized basis sets and plane-wave approaches is achieved by linearized augmented-plane-wave (LAPW) basis sets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] These are based on a partitioning of space into nonoverlapping spheres around each atom and an interstitial region in between the spheres.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] An LAPW basis function is a plane wave in the interstitial region, which is augmented by numerical atomic functions in each sphere.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The numerical atomic functions hereby provide a linearized representation of wave functions for arbitrary energies around automatically determined energy parameters.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly to plane-wave basis sets an LAPW basis set is mainly determined by a cutoff parameter for the plane-wave representation in the interstitial region.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] In the spheres the variational degrees of freedom can be extended by adding local orbitals to the basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] This allows representations of wavefunctions beyond the linearized description.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the interstitial region imply three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions, though it is possible to introduce additional augmentation regions to reduce this to one or two dimensions, e.g., for the description of chain-like structures or thin films.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The atomic-like representation in the spheres allows to treat each atom with its potential singularity at the nucleus and to not rely on a pseudopotential approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The disadvantage of LAPW basis sets is its complex definition, which comes with many parameters that have to be controlled either by the user or an automatic recipe.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Another consequence of the form of the basis set are complex mathematical expressions, e.g., for the calculation of a Hamiltonian matrix or atomic forces.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space approaches offer powerful methods to solve electronic structure problems thanks to their controllable accuracy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space basis sets can be thought to arise from the theory of interpolation, as the central idea is to represent the (unknown) orbitals in terms of some set of interpolation functions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Various methods have been proposed for constructing the solution in real space, including finite elements, basis splines, Lagrange sinc-functions, and wavelets.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Finite difference algorithms are also often included in this category, even though precisely speaking, they do not form a proper basis set and are not variational unlike e.g. finite element methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] A common feature of all real-space methods is that the accuracy of the numerical basis set is improvable, so that the complete basis set limit can be reached in a systematical manner.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] For example, in finite element methods (FEMs), the wave function is represented as a linear combination of a set of piecewise polynomials.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] Lagrange interpolating polynomials (LIPs) are a commonly used basis for FEM calculations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The local interpolation error in LIP basis of order n is of the form $h^{n+1}\max f^{(n+1)}(\xi )$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/basis-set-chemistry] The use of high-order LIPs has been shown to be highly beneficial for accuracy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In quantum chemistry and molecular physics, the **Born–Oppenheimer** (**BO**) **approximation** is the assumption that the wave functions of atomic nuclei and electrons in a molecule can be treated separately, based on the fact that the nuclei are much heavier than the electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Due to the larger relative mass of a nucleus compared to an electron, the coordinates of the nuclei in a system are approximated as fixed, while the coordinates of the electrons are dynamic.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The approach is named after Max Born and his 23-year-old graduate student J.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Robert Oppenheimer, the latter of whom proposed it in 1927 during a period of intense ferment in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The approximation is widely used in quantum chemistry to speed up the computation of molecular wavefunctions and other properties for large molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] There are cases where the assumption of separable motion no longer holds, which make the approximation lose validity (it is said to "break down"), but even then the approximation is usually used as a starting point for more refined methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energies $E_{\text{electronic}}$ consist of kinetic energies, interelectronic repulsions, internuclear repulsions, and electron–nuclear attractions, which are the terms typically included when computing the electronic structure of molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The benzene molecule consists of 12 nuclei and 42 electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The computational complexity, i.e., the computational power required to solve an eigenvalue equation, increases faster than the square of the number of coordinates.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] When applying the BO approximation, two smaller, consecutive steps can be used: For a given position of the nuclei, the *electronic* Schrödinger equation is solved, while treating the nuclei as stationary (not "coupled" with the dynamics of the electrons).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This corresponding eigenvalue problem then consists only of the 126 electronic coordinates.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This electronic computation is then repeated for other possible positions of the nuclei, i.e. deformations of the molecule.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] For benzene, this could be done using a grid of 36 possible nuclear position coordinates.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energies on this grid are then connected to give a potential energy surface for the nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This potential is then used for a second Schrödinger equation containing only the 36 coordinates of the nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In practice, the scaling of the problem is larger than $n^{2}$ , and more approximations are applied in computational chemistry to further reduce the number of variables and dimensions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The slope of the potential energy surface can be used to simulate molecular dynamics, using it to express the mean force on the nuclei caused by the electrons and thereby skipping the calculation of the nuclear Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The BO approximation recognizes the large difference between the electron mass and the masses of atomic nuclei, and correspondingly the time scales of their motion.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Given the same amount of momentum, the nuclei move much more slowly than the electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This enables a separation of the Hamiltonian operator into electronic and nuclear terms, where cross-terms between electrons and nuclei are neglected, so that the two smaller and decoupled systems can be solved more efficiently.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In the first step, the nuclear kinetic energy is neglected, that is, the corresponding operator *T*n is subtracted from the total molecular Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In the remaining electronic Hamiltonian *H*e the nuclear positions are no longer variable, but are constant parameters (they enter the equation "parametrically").
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electron–nucleus interactions are *not* removed, i.e., the electrons still "feel" the Coulomb potential of the nuclei clamped at certain positions in space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\chi (\mathbf {r} ,\mathbf {R} )$ , the electronic wavefunction for given positions of nuclei (fixed **R**), is solved approximately.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The quantity **r** stands for all electronic coordinates and **R** for all nuclear coordinates.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic energy eigenvalue *E*e depends on the chosen positions **R** of the nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Varying these positions **R** in small steps and repeatedly solving the electronic Schrödinger equation, one obtains *E*e as a function of **R**.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is the potential energy surface (PES): $E_{e}(\mathbf {R} )$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\phi (\mathbf {R} )$ is the nuclear wavefunction, is solved.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This second step of the BO approximation involves separation of vibrational, translational, and rotational motions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This can be achieved by application of the Eckart conditions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The eigenvalue *E* is the total energy of the molecule, including contributions from electrons, nuclear vibrations, and overall rotation and translation of the molecule.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In accord with the Hellmann–Feynman theorem, the nuclear potential is taken to be an average over electron configurations of the sum of the electron–nuclear and internuclear electric potentials.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] It will be discussed how the BO approximation may be derived and under which conditions it is applicable.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] At the same time we will show how the BO approximation may be improved by including vibronic coupling.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] To that end the second step of the BO approximation is generalized to a set of coupled eigenvalue equations depending on nuclear coordinates only.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Off-diagonal elements in these equations are shown to be nuclear kinetic energy terms.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The position vectors $\mathbf {r} \equiv \{\mathbf {r} _{i}\}$ of the electrons and the position vectors $\mathbf {R} \equiv \{\mathbf {R} _{A}=(R_{Ax},R_{Ay},R_{Az})\}$ of the nuclei are with respect to a Cartesian inertial frame.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Distances between particles are written as $r_{iA}\equiv |\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} _{A}|$ (distance between electron *i* and nucleus *A*) and similar definitions hold for $r_{ij}$ and $R_{AB}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] We assume that the molecule is in a homogeneous (no external force) and isotropic (no external torque) space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The only interactions are the two-body Coulomb interactions among the electrons and nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The Hamiltonian is expressed in atomic units, so that we do not see the Planck constant, the dielectric constant of the vacuum, electronic charge, or electronic mass in this formula.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The only constants explicitly entering the formula are *ZA* and *MA* – the atomic number and mass of nucleus *A*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The electronic wave functions $\chi _{k}$ will be taken to be real, which is possible when there are no magnetic or spin interactions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The *parametric dependence* of the functions $\chi _{k}$ on the nuclear coordinates is indicated by the symbol after the semicolon.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This indicates that, although $\chi _{k}$ is a real-valued function of $\mathbf {r}$ , its functional form depends on $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] For example, in the molecular-orbital-linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals (LCAO-MO) approximation, $\chi _{k}$ is a molecular orbital (MO) given as a linear expansion of atomic orbitals (AOs).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] An AO depends visibly on the coordinates of an electron, but the nuclear coordinates are not explicit in the MO.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] However, upon change of geometry, i.e., change of $\mathbf {R}$ , the LCAO coefficients obtain different values and we see corresponding changes in the functional form of the MO $\chi _{k}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] and where the subscript $(\mathbf {r} )$ indicates that the integration, implied by the bra–ket notation, is over electronic coordinates only.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The matrix $\mathbb {H} _{\text{e}}(\mathbf {R} )$ is diagonal, and the nuclear Hamilton matrix is non-diagonal; its off-diagonal (*vibronic coupling*) terms ${\big (}\mathbb {H} _{\text{n}}(\mathbf {R} ){\big )}_{k'k}$ are further discussed below.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The vibronic coupling in this approach is through nuclear kinetic energy terms.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Solution of these coupled equations gives an approximation for energy and wavefunction that goes beyond the Born–Oppenheimer approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Unfortunately, the off-diagonal kinetic energy terms are usually difficult to handle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is why often a diabatic transformation is applied, which retains part of the nuclear kinetic energy terms on the diagonal, removes the kinetic energy terms from the off-diagonal and creates coupling terms between the adiabatic PESs on the off-diagonal.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] If we can neglect the off-diagonal elements the equations will uncouple and simplify drastically.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The diagonal ( $k'=k$ ) matrix elements $\langle \chi _{k}|P_{A\alpha }|\chi _{k}\rangle _{(\mathbf {r} )}$ of the operator $P_{A\alpha }$ vanish, because we assume time-reversal invariant, so $\chi _{k}$ can be chosen to be always real.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The matrix element of the one-electron operator appearing on the right side is finite.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] When the two surfaces come close, $E_{k}(\mathbf {R} )\approx E_{k'}(\mathbf {R} )$ , the nuclear momentum coupling term becomes large and is no longer negligible.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This is the case where the BO approximation breaks down, and a coupled set of nuclear motion equations must be considered instead of the one equation appearing in the second step of the BO approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Conversely, if all surfaces are well separated, all off-diagonal terms can be neglected, and hence the whole matrix of $P_{\alpha }^{A}$ is effectively zero.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The third term on the right side of the expression for the matrix element of *T*n (the *Born–Oppenheimer diagonal correction*) can approximately be written as the matrix of $P_{\alpha }^{A}$ squared and, accordingly, is then negligible also.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] which are the normal second step of the BO equations discussed above.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] We reiterate that when two or more potential energy surfaces approach each other, or even cross, the Born–Oppenheimer approximation breaks down, and one must fall back on the coupled equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Usually one invokes then the diabatic approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] Here $|\zeta _{n}\rangle$ are eigenfunctions of the electronic Hamiltonian assumed to form a complete Hilbert space in the given region in configuration space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In order for this equation to yield a solution with the correct symmetry, it is suggested to apply a perturbation approach based on an elastic potential $u_{0}(\mathbf {q} )$ , which coincides with $u_{1}(\mathbf {q} )$ at the asymptotic region.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The equation with an elastic potential can be solved, in a straightforward manner, by substitution.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] where $\Gamma$ is an arbitrary contour, and the exponential function contains the relevant symmetry as created while moving along $\Gamma$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] In this equation the inhomogeneity ensures the symmetry for the perturbed part of the solution along any contour and therefore for the solution in the required region in configuration space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] The relevance of the present approach was demonstrated while studying a two-arrangement-channel model (containing one inelastic channel and one reactive channel) for which the two adiabatic states were coupled by a Jahn–Teller conical intersection.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] A nice fit between the symmetry-preserved single-state treatment and the corresponding two-state treatment was obtained.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] This applies in particular to the reactive state-to-state probabilities (see Table III in Ref.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/born-oppenheimer-approximation] 5b), for which the ordinary BO approximation led to erroneous results, whereas the symmetry-preserving BO approximation produced the accurate results, as they followed from solving the two coupled equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] where Ψ is usually the electronic ground state of the system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] If the expansion includes all possible CSFs of the appropriate symmetry, then this is a full configuration interaction procedure which exactly solves the electronic Schrödinger equation within the space spanned by the one-particle basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The first term in the above expansion is normally the Hartree–Fock determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The other CSFs can be characterised by the number of spin orbitals that are swapped with virtual orbitals from the Hartree–Fock determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] If only one spin orbital differs, we describe this as a single excitation determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] If two spin orbitals differ it is a double excitation determinant and so on.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] This is used to limit the number of determinants in the expansion which is called the CI-space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] Truncating the CI-space is important to save computational time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] For example, the method CID is limited to double excitations only.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The method CISD is limited to single and double excitations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] Single excitations on their own do not mix with the Hartree–Fock determinant (see Brillouin's theorem).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] These methods, CID and CISD, are in many standard programs.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The Davidson correction can be used to estimate a correction to the CISD energy to account for higher excitations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] An important problem of truncated CI methods is their size-inconsistency which means the energy of two infinitely separated particles is not double the energy of the single particle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] Slater determinants are constructed from sets of orthonormal spin orbitals, so that $\left\langle \Phi _{i}^{SO}|\Phi _{j}^{SO}\right\rangle =\delta _{ij}$ , making $\mathbb {S}$ the identity matrix and simplifying the above matrix equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The solution of the CI procedure are some eigenvalues $\mathbf {E} ^{j}$ and their corresponding eigenvectors $\mathbf {c} _{I}^{j}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] The eigenvalues are the energies of the ground and some electronically excited states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] By this it is possible to calculate energy differences (excitation energies) with CI methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] Excitation energies of truncated CI methods are generally too high, because the excited states are not that well correlated as the ground state is.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] For equally (balanced) correlation of ground and excited states (better excitation energies) one can use more than one reference determinant from which all singly, doubly, ... excited determinants are included (multireference configuration interaction).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] MRCI also gives better correlation of the ground state which is important if it has more than one dominant determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] This can be easily understood because some higher excited determinants are also taken into the CI-space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/configuration-interaction] For nearly degenerate determinants which build the ground state one should use the multi-configurational self-consistent field (MCSCF) method because the Hartree–Fock determinant is qualitatively wrong and so are the CI wave functions and energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The method was initially developed by Fritz Coester and Hermann Kümmel in the 1950s for studying nuclear-physics phenomena, but became more frequently used when in 1966 Jiří Čížek (and later together with Josef Paldus) reformulated the method for electron correlation in atoms and molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] It is now one of the most prevalent methods in quantum chemistry that includes electronic correlation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] CC theory is simply the perturbative variant of the many-electron theory (MET) of Oktay Sinanoğlu, which is the exact (and variational) solution of the many-electron problem, so it was also called "coupled-pair MET (CPMET)".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] J. Čížek used the correlation function of MET and used Goldstone-type perturbation theory to get the energy expression, while original MET was completely variational. Čížek first developed the linear CPMET and then generalized it to full CPMET in the same work in 1966.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] He then also performed an application of it on the benzene molecule with Sinanoğlu in the same year.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Because MET is somewhat difficult to perform computationally, CC is simpler and thus, in today's computational chemistry, CC is the best variant of MET and gives highly accurate results in comparison to experiments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] where H is the Hamiltonian of the system, $|\Psi \rangle$ is the exact wavefunction, and *E* is the exact energy of the ground state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Coupled-cluster theory can also be used to obtain solutions for excited states using, for example, linear-response, equation-of-motion, state-universal multi-reference, or valence-universal multi-reference coupled cluster approaches.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] where $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ is the reference wave function, which is typically a Slater determinant constructed from Hartree–Fock molecular orbitals, though other wave functions such as configuration interaction, multi-configurational self-consistent field, or Brueckner orbitals can also be used.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] T is the cluster operator, which, when acting on $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ , produces a linear combination of excited determinants from the reference wave function (see section below for greater detail).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The choice of the exponential ansatz is opportune because (unlike other ansatzes, for example, configuration interaction) it guarantees the size extensivity of the solution.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Size consistency in CC theory, also unlike other theories, does not depend on the size consistency of the reference wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] If one were to use, for example, the CCSD, or CCSD(T) levels of theory, they would not provide reasonable results for the bond breaking of F2, with the latter one approaches unphysical potential energy surfaces, though this is for reasons other than just size consistency.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] A criticism of the method is that the conventional implementation employing the similarity-transformed Hamiltonian (see below) is not variational, though there are bi-variational and quasi-variational approaches that have been developed since the first implementations of the theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] where $T_{1}$ is the operator of all single excitations, $T_{2}$ is the operator of all double excitations, and so forth.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] In the above formulae ${\hat {a}}^{a}={\hat {a}}_{a}^{\dagger }$ and ${\hat {a}}_{i}$ denote the creation and annihilation operators respectively, while *i*, *j* stand for occupied (hole) and *a*, *b* for unoccupied (particle) orbitals (states).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The creation and annihilation operators in the coupled-cluster terms above are written in canonical form, where each term is in the normal order form, with respect to the Fermi vacuum $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Applying the exponential cluster operator to the wave function, one can then generate more than doubly excited determinants due to the various powers of $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ that appear in the resulting expressions (see below).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Solving for the unknown coefficients $t_{a}^{i}$ and $t_{ab}^{ij}$ is necessary for finding the approximate solution $|\Psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Often, as was done above, the cluster operator includes only singles and doubles (see CCSD below) as this offers a computationally affordable method that performs better than MP2 and CISD, but is not very accurate usually.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] For double-bond breaking and more complicated problems in chemistry, quadruple excitations often become important as well, though usually they have small contributions for most problems, and as such, the contribution of $T_{5}$ , $T_{6}$ etc. to the operator T is typically small.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] where there are a total of *q* coefficients (*t*-amplitudes) to solve for.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] the latter being the equations to be solved, and the former the equation for the evaluation of the energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The subscript *C* designates the connected part of the corresponding operator expression.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The resulting equations are a set of non-linear equations, which are solved in an iterative manner.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Standard quantum-chemistry packages (GAMESS (US), NWChem, ACES II, etc.) solve the coupled-cluster equations using the Jacobi method and direct inversion of the iterative subspace (DIIS) extrapolation of the *t*-amplitudes to accelerate convergence.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The classification of traditional coupled-cluster methods rests on the highest number of excitations allowed in the definition of T .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Q – for quadruple excitations (*quadruples*).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Terms in round brackets indicate that these terms are calculated based on perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] An estimate to the connected triples contribution is calculated non-iteratively using many-body perturbation theory arguments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The complexity of equations and the corresponding computer codes, as well as the cost of the computation, increases sharply with the highest level of excitation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] For many applications CCSD, while relatively inexpensive, does not provide sufficient accuracy except for the smallest systems (approximately 2 to 4 electrons), and often an approximate treatment of triples is needed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The most well known coupled-cluster method that provides an estimate of connected triples is CCSD(T), which provides a good description of closed-shell molecules near the equilibrium geometry, but breaks down in more complicated situations such as bond breaking and diradicals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Another popular method that makes up for the failings of the standard CCSD(T) approach is CR-CC(2,3), where the triples contribution to the energy is computed from the difference between the exact solution and the CCSD energy and is not based on perturbation-theory arguments.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] More complicated coupled-cluster methods such as CCSDT and CCSDTQ are used only for high-accuracy calculations of small molecules.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The inclusion of all *n* levels of excitation for the *n*-electron system gives the exact solution of the Schrödinger equation within the given basis set, within the Born–Oppenheimer approximation (although schemes have also been drawn up to work without the BO approximation).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] One possible improvement to the standard coupled-cluster approach is to add terms linear in the interelectronic distances through methods such as CCSD-R12.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] This improves the treatment of dynamical electron correlation by satisfying the Kato cusp condition and accelerates convergence with respect to the orbital basis set.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Unfortunately, R12 methods invoke the resolution of the identity, which requires a relatively large basis set in order to be a good approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] The coupled-cluster method described above is also known as the *single-reference* (SR) coupled-cluster method because the exponential ansatz involves only one reference function $|\Phi _{0}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Josef Paldus also wrote his first-hand account of the origins of coupled-cluster theory, its implementation, and exploitation in electronic wave-function determination; his account is primarily about the making of coupled-cluster theory rather than about the theory itself.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Paldus, in *Methods in Computational Molecular Physics*, Vol.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] 293 of *Nato Advanced Study Institute Series B: Physics*, edited by S.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] If all of the nonlinear terms in $e^{S}$ are included, then the SAC equations become equivalent to the standard coupled-cluster equations of Jiří Čížek.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] This is due to the cancellation of the energy-dependent terms with the disconnected terms contributing to the product of $He^{S}$ , resulting in the same set of nonlinear energy-independent equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Typically, all nonlinear terms, except ${\tfrac {1}{2}}S_{2}^{2}$ are dropped, as higher-order nonlinear terms are usually small.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] In nuclear physics, coupled cluster saw significantly less use than in quantum chemistry during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] More powerful computers, as well as advances in theory (such as the inclusion of three-nucleon interactions), have spawned renewed interest in the method since then, and it has been successfully applied to neutron-rich and medium-mass nuclei.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/coupled-cluster] Coupled cluster is one of several ab initio methods in nuclear physics and is specifically suitable for nuclei having closed or nearly closed shells.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The **Schrödinger equation** is a partial differential equation that governs the wave function of a non-relativistic quantum-mechanical system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Its discovery was a significant landmark in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It is named after Erwin Schrödinger, an Austrian physicist, who postulated the equation in 1925 and published it in 1926, forming the basis for the work that resulted in his Nobel Prize in Physics in 1933.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Conceptually, the Schrödinger equation is the quantum counterpart of Newton's second law in classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Given a set of known initial conditions, Newton's second law makes a mathematical prediction as to what path a given physical system will take over time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation gives the evolution over time of the wave function, the quantum-mechanical characterization of an isolated physical system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The equation was postulated by Schrödinger based on a postulate of Louis de Broglie that all matter has an associated matter wave.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The equation predicted bound states of the atom in agreement with experimental observations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is not the only way to study quantum mechanical systems and make predictions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Other formulations of quantum mechanics include matrix mechanics, introduced by Werner Heisenberg, and the path integral formulation, developed chiefly by Richard Feynman.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] When these approaches are compared, the use of the Schrödinger equation is sometimes called "wave mechanics".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The equation given by Schrödinger is nonrelativistic because it contains a first derivative in time and a second derivative in space, and therefore space and time are not on equal footing.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Paul Dirac incorporated special relativity and quantum mechanics into a single formulation that simplifies to the Schrödinger equation in the non-relativistic limit.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is the Dirac equation, which contains a single derivative in both space and time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Another partial differential equation, the Klein–Gordon equation, led to a problem with probability density even though it was a relativistic wave equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The probability density could be negative, which is physically unviable.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This was fixed by Dirac by taking the so-called square root of the Klein–Gordon operator and in turn introducing Dirac matrices.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In a modern context, the Klein–Gordon equation describes spin-less particles, while the Dirac equation describes spin-1/2 particles.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Introductory courses on physics or chemistry typically introduce the Schrödinger equation in a way that can be appreciated knowing only the concepts and notations of basic calculus, particularly derivatives with respect to space and time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The parameter m is the mass of the particle, and $V(x,t)$ is the *potential energy function* that represents the environment in which the particle exists.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The constant i is the imaginary unit, and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant, which has units of action (energy multiplied by time).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This vector is postulated to be normalized under the Hilbert space's inner product, that is, in Dirac notation it obeys $\langle \psi |\psi \rangle =1$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Physical quantities of interest – position, momentum, energy, spin – are represented by observables, which are self-adjoint operators acting on the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A wave function can be an eigenvector of an observable, in which case it is called an eigenstate, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] More generally, a quantum state will be a linear combination of the eigenstates, known as a quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] More generally, the eigenvalue is degenerate and the probability is given by $\langle \psi |P_{\lambda }|\psi \rangle$ , where $P_{\lambda }$ is the projector onto its associated eigenspace.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A momentum eigenstate would be a perfectly monochromatic wave of infinite extent, which is not square-integrable.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Likewise a position eigenstate would be a Dirac delta distribution, not square-integrable and technically not a function at all.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, neither can belong to the particle's Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Physicists sometimes regard these eigenstates, composed of elements outside the Hilbert space, as "generalized eigenvectors".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] These are used for calculational convenience and do not represent physical states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The form of the Schrödinger equation depends on the physical situation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] where t is time, $\vert \Psi (t)\rangle$ is the state vector of the quantum system ( $\Psi$ being the Greek letter psi), and ${\hat {H}}$ is an observable, the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The term "Schrödinger equation" can refer to both the general equation, or the specific nonrelativistic version.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The general equation is indeed quite general, used throughout quantum mechanics, for everything from the Dirac equation to quantum field theory, by plugging in diverse expressions for the Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The specific nonrelativistic version is an approximation that yields accurate results in many situations, but only to a certain extent (see relativistic quantum mechanics and relativistic quantum field theory).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] To apply the Schrödinger equation, write down the Hamiltonian for the system, accounting for the kinetic and potential energies of the particles constituting the system, then insert it into the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The resulting partial differential equation is solved for the wave function, which contains information about the system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In practice, the square of the absolute value of the wave function at each point is taken to define a probability density function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The time-dependent Schrödinger equation described above predicts that wave functions can form standing waves, called stationary states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] These states are particularly important as their individual study later simplifies the task of solving the time-dependent Schrödinger equation for *any* state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is only used when the Hamiltonian itself is not dependent on time explicitly.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] However, even in this case the total wave function is dependent on time as explained in the section on linearity below.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In the language of linear algebra, this equation is an eigenvalue equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Therefore, the wave function is an eigenfunction of the Hamiltonian operator with corresponding eigenvalue(s) E .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, the sum can be extended for any number of state vectors.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This property allows superpositions of quantum states to be solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Even more generally, it holds that a general solution to the Schrödinger equation can be found by taking a weighted sum over a basis of states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A choice often employed is the basis of energy eigenstates, which are solutions of the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Unitarity is a general feature of time evolution under the Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] If the initial state is $|\Psi (0)\rangle$ , then the state at a later time t will be given by $|\Psi (t)\rangle ={\hat {U}}(t)|\Psi (0)\rangle$ for some unitary operator ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Conversely, suppose that ${\hat {U}}(t)$ is a continuous family of unitary operators parameterized by t .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Without loss of generality, the parameterization can be chosen so that ${\hat {U}}(0)$ is the identity operator and that ${\hat {U}}(t/N)^{N}={\hat {U}}(t)$ for any $N>0$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Then ${\hat {U}}(t)$ depends upon the parameter t in such a way that ${\hat {U}}(t)=e^{-i{\hat {G}}t}$ for some self-adjoint operator ${\hat {G}}$ , called the *generator* of the family ${\hat {U}}(t)$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A Hamiltonian is just such a generator (up to the factor of the Planck constant that would be set to 1 in natural units).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is often presented using quantities varying as functions of position, but as a vector-operator equation it has a valid representation in any arbitrary complete basis of kets in Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] As mentioned above, "bases" that lie outside the physical Hilbert space are also employed for calculational purposes.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is illustrated by the *position-space* and *momentum-space* Schrödinger equations for a nonrelativistic, spinless particle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] When restricted from three dimensions to one, the position-space equation is just the first form of the Schrödinger equation given above.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The relation between position and momentum in quantum mechanics can be appreciated in a single dimension.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Thus, ${\hat {p}}^{2}$ becomes a second derivative, and in three dimensions, the second derivative becomes the Laplacian $\nabla ^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The canonical commutation relation also implies that the position and momentum operators are Fourier conjugates of each other.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Consequently, functions originally defined in terms of their position dependence can be converted to functions of momentum using the Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In solid-state physics, the Schrödinger equation is often written for functions of momentum, as Bloch's theorem ensures the periodic crystal lattice potential couples ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p)$ with ${\tilde {\Psi }}(p+\hbar K)$ for only discrete reciprocal lattice vectors K .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This makes it convenient to solve the momentum-space Schrödinger equation at each point in the Brillouin zone independently of the other points in the Brillouin zone.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation is consistent with local probability conservation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It also ensures that a normalized wavefunction remains normalized after time evolution.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In matrix mechanics, this means that the time evolution operator is a unitary operator.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In contrast to, for example, the Klein Gordon equation, although a redefined inner product of a wavefunction can be time independent, the total volume integral of modulus square of the wavefunction need not be time independent.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Although the factor ${\textstyle {\nabla S}/{m}}$ appears to play the role of velocity, it does not represent velocity at a point since simultaneous measurement of position and velocity violates uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The spatial part of the full wave function solves the equation $\nabla ^{2}\psi (\mathbf {r} )+{\frac {2m}{\hbar ^{2}}}\left[E-V(\mathbf {r} )\right]\psi (\mathbf {r} )=0,$ where the energy E appears in the phase factor.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This generalizes to any number of particles in any number of dimensions (in a time-independent potential): the standing wave solutions of the time-independent equation are the states with definite energy, instead of a probability distribution of different energies.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In physics, these standing waves are called "stationary states" or "energy eigenstates"; in chemistry they are called "atomic orbitals" or "molecular orbitals".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Superpositions of energy eigenstates change their properties according to the relative phases between the energy levels.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The energy eigenstates form a basis: any wave function may be written as a sum over the discrete energy states or an integral over continuous energy states, or more generally as an integral over a measure.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is an example of the spectral theorem, and in a finite-dimensional state space it is just a statement of the completeness of the eigenvectors of a Hermitian matrix.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Separation of variables can also be a useful method for the time-independent Schrödinger equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The particle in a one-dimensional potential energy box is the most mathematically simple example where restraints lead to the quantization of energy levels.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The box is defined as having zero potential energy *inside* a certain region and infinite potential energy *outside*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] With the differential operator defined by ${\hat {p}}_{x}=-i\hbar {\frac {d}{dx}}$ the previous equation is evocative of the classic kinetic energy analogue, ${\frac {1}{2m}}{\hat {p}}_{x}^{2}=E,$ with state $\psi$ in this case having energy E coincident with the kinetic energy of the particle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The infinite potential walls of the box determine the values of $C,D,$ and k at $x=0$ and $x=L$ where $\psi$ must be zero.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] At $x=L$ , $\psi (L)=0=C\sin(kL),$ in which C cannot be zero as this would conflict with the postulate that $\psi$ has norm 1.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A finite potential well is the generalization of the infinite potential well problem to potential wells having finite depth.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The finite potential well problem is mathematically more complicated than the infinite particle-in-a-box problem as the wave function is not pinned to zero at the walls of the well.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Instead, the wave function must satisfy more complicated mathematical boundary conditions as it is nonzero in regions outside the well.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Another related problem is that of the rectangular potential barrier, which furnishes a model for the quantum tunneling effect that plays an important role in the performance of modern technologies such as flash memory and scanning tunneling microscopy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Furthermore, it can be used to describe approximately a wide variety of other systems, including vibrating atoms, molecules, and atoms or ions in lattices, and approximating other potentials near equilibrium points.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It is also the basis of perturbation methods in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The case $n=0$ is called the ground state, its energy is called the zero-point energy, and the wave function is a Gaussian.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The harmonic oscillator, like the particle in a box, illustrates the generic feature of the Schrödinger equation that the energies of bound eigenstates are discretized.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The negative sign arises in the potential term since the proton and electron are oppositely charged.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The reduced mass in place of the electron mass is used since the electron and proton together orbit each other about a common center of mass, and constitute a two-body problem to solve.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The motion of the electron is of principal interest here, so the equivalent one-body problem is the motion of the electron using the reduced mass.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation for a hydrogen atom can be solved by separation of variables.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In this case, spherical polar coordinates are the most convenient.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Thus, $\psi (r,\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )=R(r)\ \Theta (\theta )\ \Phi (\varphi ),$ where *R* are radial functions and $Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ are spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ and order m .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is the only atom for which the Schrödinger equation has been solved exactly.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Multi-electron atoms require approximate methods.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It is typically not possible to solve the Schrödinger equation exactly for situations of physical interest.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Accordingly, approximate solutions are obtained using techniques like variational methods and WKB approximation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It is also common to treat a problem of interest as a small modification to a problem that can be solved exactly, a method known as perturbation theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] One simple way to compare classical to quantum mechanics is to consider the time-evolution of the *expected* position and *expected* momentum, which can then be compared to the time-evolution of the ordinary position and momentum in classical mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The quantum expectation values satisfy the Ehrenfest theorem.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] For a general $V'$ , therefore, quantum mechanics can lead to predictions where expectation values do not mimic the classical behavior.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In the case of the quantum harmonic oscillator, however, $V'$ is linear and this distinction disappears, so that in this very special case, the expected position and expected momentum do exactly follow the classical trajectories.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] For general systems, the best we can hope for is that the expected position and momentum will *approximately* follow the classical trajectories.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] If the wave function is highly concentrated around a point $x_{0}$ , then $V'\left(\left\langle X\right\rangle \right)$ and $\left\langle V'(X)\right\rangle$ will be *almost* the same, since both will be approximately equal to $V'(x_{0})$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In that case, the expected position and expected momentum will remain very close to the classical trajectories, at least for as long as the wave function remains highly localized in position.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Here the generalized coordinates $q_{i}$ for $i=1,2,3$ (used in the context of the HJE) can be set to the position in Cartesian coordinates as $\mathbf {r} =(q_{1},q_{2},q_{3})=(x,y,z)$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Substituting $\Psi ={\sqrt {\rho (\mathbf {r} ,t)}}e^{iS(\mathbf {r} ,t)/\hbar }$ where $\rho$ is the probability density, into the Schrödinger equation and then taking the limit $\hbar \to 0$ in the resulting equation yield the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Wave functions are not always the most convenient way to describe quantum systems and their behavior.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] When the preparation of a system is only imperfectly known, or when the system under investigation is a part of a larger whole, density matrices may be used instead.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A density matrix is a positive semi-definite operator whose trace is equal to 1.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] (The term "density operator" is also used, particularly when the underlying Hilbert space is infinite-dimensional.) The set of all density matrices is convex, and the extreme points are the operators that project onto vectors in the Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The density-matrix analogue of the Schrödinger equation for wave functions is $i\hbar {\frac {\partial {\hat {\rho }}}{\partial t}}=[{\hat {H}},{\hat {\rho }}],$ where the brackets denote a commutator.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is variously known as the von Neumann equation, the Liouville–von Neumann equation, or just the Schrödinger equation for density matrices.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Unitary evolution of a density matrix conserves its von Neumann entropy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The one-particle Schrödinger equation described above is valid only in the nonrelativistic domain.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The effect of a Galilean transformation upon the Schrödinger equation can be creates a phase factor times the wave function, but the probabilities, as calculated via the Born rule, are unchanged.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] But the time coordinate in the Schrödinger equation is not proper time and relativistic effects on mass are absent.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Moreover, processes that change particle number are natural in relativity, and so an equation for one particle (or any fixed number thereof) can only be of limited use.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A more general form of the Schrödinger equation that also applies in relativistic situations can be formulated within quantum field theory (QFT), a framework that allows the combination of quantum mechanics with special relativity.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The region in which both simultaneously apply may be described by relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Such descriptions may use time evolution generated by a Hamiltonian operator, as in the Schrödinger functional method.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Attempts to combine quantum physics with special relativity began with building relativistic wave equations from the relativistic energy–momentum relation $E^{2}=(pc)^{2}+\left(m_{0}c^{2}\right)^{2},$ instead of nonrelativistic energy equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Klein–Gordon equation and the Dirac equation are two such equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Historically, Dirac obtained the Dirac equation by seeking a differential equation that would be first-order in both time and space, a desirable property for a relativistic theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Taking the "square root" of the left-hand side of the Klein–Gordon equation in this way required factorizing it into a product of two operators, which Dirac wrote using 4 × 4 matrices $\alpha _{1},\alpha _{2},\alpha _{3},\beta$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This has again the form of the Schrödinger equation, with the time derivative of the wave function being given by a Hamiltonian operator acting upon the wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Including influences upon the particle requires modifying the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Dirac equation is true for all spin-1⁄2 particles, and the solutions to the equation are 4-component spinor fields with two components corresponding to the particle and the other two for the antiparticle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] For the Klein–Gordon equation, the general form of the Schrödinger equation is inconvenient to use, and in practice the Hamiltonian is not expressed in an analogous way to the Dirac Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In general, the Hamiltonian to be substituted in the general Schrödinger equation is not just a function of the position and momentum operators (and possibly time), but also of spin matrices.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Also, the solutions to a relativistic wave equation, for a massive particle of spin *s*, are complex-valued 2(2*s* + 1)-component spinor fields.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] As originally formulated, the Dirac equation is an equation for a single quantum particle, just like the single-particle Schrödinger equation with wave function $\Psi (x,t)$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This is of limited use in relativistic quantum mechanics, where particle number is not fixed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Heuristically, this complication can be motivated by noting that mass–energy equivalence implies material particles can be created from energy.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] A common way to address this in QFT is to introduce a Hilbert space where the basis states are labeled by particle number, a so-called Fock space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation can then be formulated for quantum states on this Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] However, because the Schrödinger equation picks out a preferred time axis, the Lorentz invariance of the theory is no longer manifest, and accordingly, the theory is often formulated in other ways.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Following Max Planck's quantization of light (see black-body radiation), Albert Einstein interpreted Planck's quanta to be photons, particles of light, and proposed that the energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency, one of the first signs of wave–particle duality.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Louis de Broglie hypothesized that this is true for all particles, even particles which have mass such as electrons.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] He showed that, assuming that the matter waves propagate along with their particle counterparts, electrons form standing waves, meaning that only certain discrete rotational frequencies about the nucleus of an atom are allowed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] These quantized orbits correspond to discrete energy levels, and de Broglie reproduced the Bohr model formula for the energy levels.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This approach essentially confined the electron wave in one dimension, along a circular orbit of radius r .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Lunn at the University of Chicago had used the same argument based on the completion of the relativistic energy–momentum 4-vector to derive what we now call the de Broglie relation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Following up on de Broglie's ideas, physicist Peter Debye made an offhand comment that if particles behaved as waves, they should satisfy some sort of wave equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Inspired by Debye's remark, Schrödinger decided to find a proper 3-dimensional wave equation for the electron.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] By that time Arnold Sommerfeld had refined the Bohr model with relativistic corrections.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] He found the standing waves of this relativistic equation, but the relativistic corrections disagreed with Sommerfeld's formula.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Discouraged, he put away his calculations and secluded himself with a mistress in a mountain cabin in December 1925.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] While at the cabin, Schrödinger decided that his earlier nonrelativistic calculations were novel enough to publish and decided to leave off the problem of relativistic corrections for the future.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Despite the difficulties in solving the differential equation for hydrogen (he had sought help from his friend the mathematician Hermann Weyl) Schrödinger showed that his nonrelativistic version of the wave equation produced the correct spectral energies of hydrogen in a paper published in 1926.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger computed the hydrogen spectral series by treating a hydrogen atom's electron as a wave $\Psi (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ , moving in a potential well V , created by the proton.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This computation accurately reproduced the energy levels of the Bohr model.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation details the behavior of $\Psi$ but says nothing of its *nature*.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger tried to interpret the real part of $\Psi {\frac {\partial \Psi ^{*}}{\partial t}}$ as a charge density, and then revised this proposal, saying in his next paper that the modulus squared of $\Psi$ is a charge density.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This approach was, however, unsuccessful.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In 1926, just a few days after this paper was published, Max Born successfully interpreted $\Psi$ as the probability amplitude, whose modulus squared is equal to probability density.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation provides a way to calculate the wave function of a system and how it changes dynamically in time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] However, the Schrödinger equation does not directly say *what,* exactly, the wave function is.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The meaning of the Schrödinger equation and how the mathematical entities in it relate to physical reality depends upon the interpretation of quantum mechanics that one adopts.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] In the views often grouped together as the Copenhagen interpretation, a system's wave function is a collection of statistical information about that system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The Schrödinger equation relates information about the system at one time to information about it at another.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The wave function changes, according to this school of thought, because new information is available.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The post-measurement wave function generally cannot be known prior to the measurement, but the probabilities for the different possibilities can be calculated using the Born rule.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Other, more recent interpretations of quantum mechanics, such as relational quantum mechanics and QBism, view the Schrödinger equation in a similar way.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Schrödinger himself suggested in 1952 that the different terms of a superposition evolving under the Schrödinger equation are "not alternatives but all really happen simultaneously".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This has been interpreted as an early version of Everett's many-worlds interpretation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation, formulated independently in 1956, holds that *all* the possibilities described by quantum theory *simultaneously* occur in a multiverse composed of mostly independent parallel universes.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] This interpretation removes the axiom of wave function collapse, leaving only continuous evolution under the Schrödinger equation, and so all possible states of the measured system and the measuring apparatus, together with the observer, are present in a real physical quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] While the multiverse is deterministic, we perceive non-deterministic behavior governed by probabilities, because we do not observe the multiverse as a whole, but only one parallel universe at a time.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Exactly how this is supposed to work has been the subject of much debate.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Why should we assign probabilities at all to outcomes that are certain to occur in some worlds, and why should the probabilities be given by the Born rule?
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Several ways to answer these questions in the many-worlds framework have been proposed, but there is no consensus on whether they are successful.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] Bohmian mechanics reformulates quantum mechanics to make it deterministic, at the price of adding a force due to a "quantum potential".
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] It attributes to each physical system not only a wave function but in addition a real position that evolves deterministically under a nonlocal guiding equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/schrödinger-equation] The evolution of a physical system is given at all times by the Schrödinger equation together with the guiding equation.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In quantum mechanics, a **Slater determinant** is an expression that describes the wave function of a multi-fermionic system.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] It satisfies anti-symmetry requirements, and consequently the Pauli principle, by changing sign upon exchange of two fermions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Only a small subset of all possible many-body fermionic wave functions can be written as a single Slater determinant, but those form an important and useful subset because of their simplicity.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The Slater determinant arises from the consideration of a wave function for a collection of electrons, each with a wave function known as the spin-orbital $\chi (\mathbf {x} )$ , where $\mathbf {x}$ denotes the position and spin of a single electron.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] A Slater determinant containing two electrons with the same spin orbital would correspond to a wave function that is zero everywhere.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The Slater determinant is named for John C.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Slater, who introduced the determinant in 1929 as a means of ensuring the antisymmetry of a many-electron wave function, although the wave function in the determinant form first appeared independently in Heisenberg's and Dirac's articles three years earlier.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The simplest way to approximate the wave function of a many-particle system is to take the product of properly chosen orthogonal wave functions of the individual particles.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] This expression is used in the Hartree method as an ansatz for the many-particle wave function and is known as a Hartree product.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] However, it is not satisfactory for fermions because the wave function above is not antisymmetric under exchange of any two of the fermions, as it must be according to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] This does not hold for the Hartree product, which therefore does not satisfy the Pauli principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] where the coefficient is the normalization factor.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] This wave function is now antisymmetric and no longer distinguishes between fermions (that is, one cannot indicate an ordinal number to a specific particle, and the indices given are interchangeable).
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Moreover, it also goes to zero if any two spin orbitals of two fermions are the same.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] This is equivalent to satisfying the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The expression can be generalised to any number of fermions by writing it as a determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] where the last two expressions use a shorthand for Slater determinants: The normalization constant is implied by noting the number N, and only the one-particle wavefunctions (first shorthand) or the indices for the fermion coordinates (second shorthand) are written down.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] All skipped labels are implied to behave in ascending sequence.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The linear combination of Hartree products for the two-particle case is identical with the Slater determinant for *N* = 2.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The use of Slater determinants ensures an antisymmetrized function at the outset.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In the same way, the use of Slater determinants ensures conformity to the Pauli principle.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Indeed, the Slater determinant vanishes if the set $\{\chi _{i}\}$ is linearly dependent.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In particular, this is the case when two (or more) spin orbitals are the same.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In chemistry one expresses this fact by stating that no two electrons with the same spin can occupy the same spatial orbital.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Many properties of the Slater determinant come to life with an example in a non-relativistic many electron problem.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] and where we will distinguish in the Hamiltonian between the first set of terms as ${\hat {G}}_{1}$ (the "1" particle terms) and the last term ${\hat {G}}_{2}$ (the "2" particle term) which contains exchange term for a Slater determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The two parts will behave differently when they have to interact with a Slater determinant wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In the above expression, we can just select the identical permutation in the determinant in the left part, since all the other N! − 1 permutations would give the same result as the selected one.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] This result shows that the anti-symmetrization of the product does not have any effect for the one particle terms and it behaves as it would do in the case of the simple Hartree product.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Which tells us that to the extent of the one-particle terms the wave functions of the electrons are independent of each other and the expectation value of total system is given by the sum of expectation value of the single particles.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The first contribution is called the "coulomb" term or "coulomb" integral and the second is the "exchange" term or exchange integral.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Sometimes different range of index in the summation is used ${\textstyle \sum _{ij}}$ since the Coulomb and exchange contributions exactly cancel each other for $i=j$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] It is important to notice explicitly that the exchange term, which is always positive for local spin-orbitals, is absent in the simple Hartree product.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Hence the electron-electron repulsive energy $\langle \Psi _{0}|G_{2}|\Psi _{0}\rangle$ on the antisymmetrized product of spin-orbitals is always lower than the electron-electron repulsive energy on the simple Hartree product of the same spin-orbitals.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Since exchange bielectronic integrals are different from zero only for spin-orbitals with parallel spins, we link the decrease in energy with the physical fact that electrons with parallel spin are kept apart in real space in Slater determinant states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The space of all pure quantum states in a Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ can be identified with a projective Hilbert space, the manifold of all 1-dimensional subspaces of ${\mathcal {H}}$ , since states differing by a global phase represent the same physical state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] A Slater determinant in the tensor product ${\mathcal {H}}^{\otimes N}$ is uniquely determined, up to a global phase, by the N -dimensional subspace of ${\mathcal {H}}$ spanned by the corresponding one-particle states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The space of states that can be written as a single Slater determinant in ${\mathcal {H}}$ forms a smooth manifold and projective algebraic variety which is naturally identified with the Grassmannian $\mathbf {Gr} _{N}({\mathcal {H}})$ .
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Its embedding into the projective many-particle Hilbert space $\mathbf {P} ({\mathcal {H}}^{\otimes N})$ is equivalent to the Plücker embedding, which corresponds exactly to taking the many-particle Slater determinant of a given set of N one-particle states.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In quantum chemistry, the geometric structure of these spaces plays an important role in theoretical analysis of the Hartree-Fock method and can be used to prove theoretical results on the existence of solutions to the Hartree-Fock equations.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Most fermionic wavefunctions cannot be represented as a Slater determinant.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The best Slater approximation to a given fermionic wave function can be defined to be the one that maximizes the overlap between the Slater determinant and the target wave function.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] The maximal overlap is a geometric measure of entanglement between the fermions.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] A single Slater determinant is used as an approximation to the electronic wavefunction in Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] In more accurate theories (such as configuration interaction and MCSCF), a linear combination of Slater determinants is needed.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Boys to refer to a Slater determinant of orthonormal orbitals, but this term is rarely used.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Unlike fermions that are subject to the Pauli exclusion principle, two or more bosons can occupy the same single-particle quantum state.
[src:quantum-chemistry-methods/slater-determinant] Wavefunctions describing systems of identical bosons are symmetric under the exchange of particles and can be expanded in terms of permanents.
